# Project Roadmap


#Sprint 1

## Codebase Abandoned

The first codebase I found turned out to be far too complex for me to realistically work with. It was severely outdated and required a large number of external dependencies.

Over the course of two to three days, I tried everything I could to get it running:

- Downloaded dependency after dependency

- Adjusted Windows PowerShell settings to allow third‑party scripts

- Installed an older version of Python to match the obsolete requirements

Even after all of that, the project still wouldn’t run. At that point, I decided it was better to start over with a more modern and manageable codebase.


## Codebase Search pt 2.

I refined my search to focus specifically on to‑do list projects created within the last five years that did not rely on heavy frameworks like Django or Flask.

This led me to a Tkinter‑based to‑do list application, which ran successfully on the very first attempt. Since Tkinter is built into Python, it required no external installations and was much easier to work with.


## What I learned from the codebase, what it does, etc

How it works is that a window is created and the code runs so that the UI features operational buttons used for features including: 

- delete

- clear

- save

- open

- add

Where it says class window is where the window size, color, and other features are declared.

My understanding of the the rest of the programming is questionable so until I conduct more research, I will only definitively commit to using the Class window section of code as a reference for a part of my own project.


## Sprint 2

For Sprint 2, I will begin developing to‑do list application. I plan to start with a simple version and perhaps expand it if time and... ability permit.

### Core features I will build first
- Add a task  
- View all tasks  
- Delete a task  

These features will give me a working bare minimum version of the app and it will be directly influenced by the codebase I found

### Features I may consider later
- Saving tasks to a file  
- Editing existing tasks  
- Adding due dates or categories  
- Improving the UI layout  

### Tools and approach
I will use Python and Tkinter, since the codebase I explored showed me how effective Tkinter can be without the use of numerous third-party dependencies. I will commit to GitHub to show progress.


